---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Pattern Speed - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Pattern Speed</h1>
        
        <div class="infobox">
            <h3 class="infobox-title">Pattern Speed</h3>
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Symbol:</th>
                    <td>Ω<sub>p</sub></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Units:</th>
                    <td>km/s/kpc</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type:</th>
                    <td>Kinematic property</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Related:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Corotation_Radius" text="Corotation Radius" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Lindblad_Resonances" text="Lindblad Resonances" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Bar_Formation" text="Bar Formation" /></td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>

        <p>The <strong>pattern speed</strong> (Ω<sub>p</sub>) is the angular velocity at which a non-axisymmetric structure (such as a <WikiLink slug="pages/Barred_Galaxies" text="bar" /> or <WikiLink slug="pages/Spiral_Arms" text="spiral arms" />) rotates in a galaxy. It is a fundamental parameter in galactic dynamics that determines the locations of important <WikiLink slug="pages/Resonances" text="resonances" /> and influences gas flows, star formation, and <WikiLink slug="pages/Secular_Evolution" text="secular evolution" />.</p>

        <h2 id="section-0">Definition</h2>
        
        <p>For a bar or spiral pattern, the pattern speed is defined as:</p>
        
        <p style="text-align: center;">Ω<sub>p</sub> = dφ<sub>bar</sub>/dt</p>
        
        <p>where φ<sub>bar</sub> is the position angle of the pattern. In practice, it is often measured through <WikiLink slug="pages/Fourier_Analysis" text="Fourier analysis" /> of the m=2 component for bars.</p>

        <h2 id="section-1">Measurement Techniques</h2>
        
        <h3>Observational Methods</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Tremaine-Weinberg_Method" text="Tremaine-Weinberg method" /> - Uses continuity equation</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Font-Beckman_Method" text="Font-Beckman method" /> - Based on gas kinematics</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Model_Fitting" text="Model fitting" /> - Matches simulations to observations</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Simulation Methods</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Direct tracking of bar/spiral angle evolution</li>
            <li>Fourier decomposition of density field<sup>[1]</sup></li>
            <li>Following test particles in pattern reference frame</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-2">Evolution of Pattern Speed</h2>

        <h3>Initial Pattern Speed</h3>
        <p>The initial pattern speed of bars depends on:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Disk properties (mass, scale length, velocity dispersion)</li>
            <li>Presence and properties of <WikiLink slug="pages/Classical_Bulges" text="classical bulges" /><sup>[1]</sup></li>
            <li>Dark matter halo properties</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="evidence-for">
            <h4>Effect of Bulges on Initial Ω<sub>p</sub></h4>
            <p>More massive/compact bulges lead to:<sup>[1]</sup></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Higher circular velocities in central regions</li>
                <li>Higher initial pattern speeds at bar formation</li>
                <li>Faster subsequent deceleration rates</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>Pattern Speed Deceleration</h3>
        <p>Bars typically slow down over time due to:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Dynamical_Friction" text="Dynamical friction" /> with the dark matter halo</li>
            <li>Angular momentum transfer to disk stars</li>
            <li>Gas inflow and central mass buildup</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-3">Fast vs. Slow Bars</h2>
        
        <p>Bars are classified based on their dimensionless rotation rate <WikiLink slug="pages/R_Parameter" text="R" /> = R<sub>CR</sub>/R<sub>bar</sub>:</p>
        
        <table style="width: 80%; margin: 1em auto;">
            <tr>
                <th>Type</th>
                <th>R value</th>
                <th>Characteristics</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Fast bars</td>
                <td>R &lt; 1.4</td>
                <td>Corotation near bar end</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Slow bars</td>
                <td>R > 1.4</td>
                <td>Corotation well beyond bar</td>
            </tr>
        </table>

        <h2 id="section-4">Pattern Speed in Different Contexts</h2>

        <h3>During Bar Formation</h3>
        <p>Studies show that during the formation stage:<sup>[1]</sup></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Bars exhibit exponential growth in strength</li>
            <li>Pattern speed starts high and decelerates</li>
            <li>Bulge properties strongly influence Ω<sub>p</sub></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Secular Evolution Stage</h3>
        <p>In the secular growth phase:<sup>[1]</sup></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Pattern speed evolution dominated by disk properties</li>
            <li>Bulge influence becomes less significant</li>
            <li>Similar Ω<sub>p</sub>-A<sub>2</sub> relations regardless of bulge</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-5">Resonances</h2>
        
        <p>The pattern speed determines the locations of key resonances:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Corotation_Resonance" text="Corotation" />: Ω = Ω<sub>p</sub></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Inner_Lindblad_Resonance" text="Inner Lindblad Resonance" />: Ω - κ/2 = Ω<sub>p</sub></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Outer_Lindblad_Resonance" text="Outer Lindblad Resonance" />: Ω + κ/2 = Ω<sub>p</sub></li>
        </ul>

        <p>where κ is the <WikiLink slug="pages/Epicyclic_Frequency" text="epicyclic frequency" />.</p>

        <h2 id="section-6">Implications</h2>

        <h3>For Galaxy Evolution</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Controls gas flow patterns and star formation</li>
            <li>Determines effectiveness of angular momentum transport</li>
            <li>Influences <WikiLink slug="pages/Pseudobulge_Formation" text="pseudobulge formation" /></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>For Observations</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Pattern speed measurements constrain dark matter distribution</li>
            <li>Fast/slow bar dichotomy tests formation theories</li>
            <li>Evolution of Ω<sub>p</sub> traces merger history</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-7">Open Questions</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Can bars maintain constant pattern speeds?</li>
            <li>What sets the initial pattern speed?</li>
            <li>How do multiple patterns (bar + spiral) interact?</li>
            <li>Is pattern speed evolution reversible?</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-8">See Also</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Bar_Formation" text="Bar Formation" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Corotation_Radius" text="Corotation Radius" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Tremaine-Weinberg_Method" text="Tremaine-Weinberg Method" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Fast_Slow_Bars" text="Fast and Slow Bars" /></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-9">References</h2>
        <ol class="references">
            <li>Zheng et al. (2026) - "Comparison of Bar Formation Mechanisms. IIIA. The role of classical bulges in spontaneous bar formation" arXiv:2603.12121</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="page-tags">
            <strong>Tags:</strong>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Dynamics" text="Dynamics" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Kinematics" text="Kinematics" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Bar_Properties" text="Bar Properties" />
        </div>
  </main>
</Base>
